Data Preparation

myData = read.csv("~/Desktop/BostonData2.csv")
myData = myData[, -1]
bos3 = read.csv("~/Desktop/BostonData3.csv")
bos3 = bos3[, -1]
#names(myData)

Some algorithms need the matrix/vector input (instead of a data frame). Here the X matrix is loaded (3 subscripts are for the boston3 dataset)

X = data.matrix(myData[,-1])  
Y = myData[,1]
X3 = data.matrix(bos3[,-1])  
Y3 = bos3[,1]

We will repeat the following simulation 50 times. In each iteration, randomly split the data into two parts, 75% for training and 25% for testing.

You can write a loop with 50 iterations, and in each iteration, split the data and run the seven procedures (six procedures for BostonData3.csv).

Or you can save the row IDs for the 50 test datasets, then write a separate loop for each method. Using all.test.id (produced below), you can ensure that you use the same training/test split for each procedure.

T = 50
n = length(Y)
ntest = round(n * 0.25)  # test set size
ntrain = n - ntest  # training set size
all.test.id = matrix(0, ntest, T)  # 
for(t in 1:T){
  all.test.id[, t] = sample(1:n, ntest)
}
#save(all.test.id, file="alltestID.RData")

Simulation

first creating a MSPE matrix for Boston2 data and Boston3 data.

mspe=matrix(0, 7, T)
mspe3=matrix(0, 6, T)

names(mspe) = c("Full", "R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR")
names(mspe3) = c("R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR")

Full Model

Running the full model on Boston 2:

for(t in 1:T){
  test.id = all.test.id[,t]
  full.model = lm(Y ~ ., data = myData[-test.id,])
  Ytest.pred = predict(full.model, newdata = myData[test.id,])
  mspe[1,t] = mean((myData$Y[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
}

Ridge

Ridge from code provided.

cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 0)
best.lam = cv.out$lambda.min

The output below is zero, which means that best.lam is the smallest lambda value in the default lambda sequence used by cv.glmnet. If so, we need to include some lambda values that are smaller than best.lam in order to see the U shape CV plot.

sum(cv.out$lambda < best.lam)
## [1] 0
plot(cv.out)

Based on the CV plot, we provide a new lambda sequence as follows.

#the following is the lambda sequence for boston data 2
lambda.b2 = exp(seq(-7, -4, length.out = 100))
cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 0, 
                   lambda = lambda.b2)
plot(cv.out)

Based on the CV plot, we have to keep decreasing lambda values. Eventually, we use the following lambda sequence for our full simulation.

lambda.b2 = exp(seq(-10, -2, length.out = 100))
cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 0, 
                   lambda = lambda.b2)
plot(cv.out)

For the boston 3 data we will be using the following Lamda sequence for our simulation:

lambda.b3 = exp(seq(-2, 2, length.out = 100))
cv.out = cv.glmnet(X3[-test.id, ], Y3[-test.id], alpha = 0,lambda = lambda.b3 )
plot(cv.out)

Lasso to confirm lambda sequence

cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 1)

plot(cv.out)

..and for boston 3

cv.out = cv.glmnet(X3[-test.id, ], Y3[-test.id], alpha = 1)
plot(cv.out)

#simulation loop
for(t in 1:T){
  test.id = all.test.id[,t]
  #ridge on Boston 2
  cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 0, 
                   lambda = lambda.b2)
  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.min
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X[test.id, ])
  mspe[2,t] = mean((Y[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)

  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.1se
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X[test.id, ])
  mspe[3,t] = mean((Y[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)
  #ridge on Boston 3
  cv.out = cv.glmnet(X3[-test.id, ], Y3[-test.id], alpha = 0, 
                   lambda = lambda.b3)
  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.min
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X3[test.id, ])
  mspe3[1,t] = mean((Y3[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)

  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.1se
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X3[test.id, ])
  mspe3[2,t] = mean((Y3[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
  #lasso on Boston 2
  cv.out = cv.glmnet(X[-test.id, ], Y[-test.id], alpha = 1)
  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.min
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X[test.id, ])
  mspe[4,t] = mean((Y[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)

  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.1se
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X[test.id, ])
  mspe[5,t] = mean((Y[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
  mylasso.coef = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, type = "coefficients")
  var.sel = row.names(mylasso.coef)[which(mylasso.coef != 0)[-1]]
  mylasso.refit = lm(Y ~ ., myData[-test.id, c("Y", var.sel)])
  Ytest.pred = predict(mylasso.refit, newdata = myData[test.id, ])
  mspe[6,t] = mean((Ytest.pred - Y[test.id])^2)
  
  #lasso on Boston 3
  cv.out = cv.glmnet(X3[-test.id, ], Y3[-test.id], alpha = 1)
  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.min
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X3[test.id, ])
  mspe3[3,t] = mean((Y3[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)

  best.lam = cv.out$lambda.1se
  Ytest.pred = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, newx = X3[test.id, ])
  mspe3[4,t] = mean((Y3[test.id] - Ytest.pred)^2)
  
  mylasso.coef = predict(cv.out, s = best.lam, type = "coefficients")
  var.sel = row.names(mylasso.coef)[which(mylasso.coef != 0)[-1]]
  mylasso.refit = lm(Y ~ ., bos3[-test.id, c("Y", var.sel)])
  Ytest.pred = predict(mylasso.refit, newdata = bos3[test.id, ])
  mspe3[5,t] = mean((Ytest.pred - Y3[test.id])^2)
  
  #pcr on Boston 2
  mypcr = pcr(Y ~ ., data= myData[-test.id, ], validation="CV")
  CVerr = RMSEP(mypcr)$val[1, , ]
  adjCVerr = RMSEP(mypcr)$val[2, , ]
  best.ncomp = which.min(CVerr) - 1 
  best.ncomp
  
  if (best.ncomp==0) {
      Ytest.pred = mean(myData$Y[-test.id])
    } else {
      Ytest.pred = predict(mypcr, myData[test.id,], ncomp=best.ncomp)
    }
  
  mspe[7,t] = mean((Ytest.pred - myData$Y[test.id])^2)
  
  #pcr on Boston 3
  mypcr = pcr(Y ~ ., data= bos3[-test.id, ], validation="CV")
  CVerr = RMSEP(mypcr)$val[1, , ]
  adjCVerr = RMSEP(mypcr)$val[2, , ]
  best.ncomp = which.min(CVerr) - 1 
  best.ncomp
  
  if (best.ncomp==0) {
      Ytest.pred = mean(bos3$Y[-test.id])
    } else {
      Ytest.pred = predict(mypcr, bos3[test.id,], ncomp=best.ncomp)
    }
  
  mspe3[6,t] = mean((Ytest.pred - bos3$Y[test.id])^2)  
}

Results

Now we present the two simulations results for Boston 2 and Boston 3 datasets. The PCR result perormed markedly worse relative to its competitors in Boston 3 dataset.

boxplot.matrix(mspe,use.cols = FALSE,main="MSPE for Seven Procedures on Boston 2",
   xlab="Procedure", ylab="Mean-SQ err",names= c("Full", "R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR"))

boxplot.matrix(mspe3,use.cols = FALSE,main="MSPE for Six Procedures on Boston 3",
   xlab="Procedure", ylab="Mean-SQ err",names= c( "R_min", "R_1se", "L_min", "L_1se", "L_Refit", "PCR"))
